"0990–1097","1024":"1024","0990":"0990","1044":"1044","1021":"1021","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","about 1043":"about 1043","1092":"1092","Glenham, Lincolnshire England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Le Quesney, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandy, France":"Le Quesney, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chesnay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and Irish (Antrim, Down): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (an) tSasanaigh</b>, see   McChesney  .","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Chaney  , a cognate of 3 below.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by or in an oak wood, from Old French <i>chesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (from <i>chesne</i> ‘oak’). Compare   Cheney   2."],"variants":[{"name":"McChesney","meanings":["Scottish (Galloway) and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (an) tSasanaigh</b> ‘son of the Saxon (i.e. the Englishman)’. The spelling seems to represent <i>Mac Shasanaigh</i>, to be pronounced originally as <i>McHasney</i>, rather than the English spelling <i>ch</i>."]},{"name":"Chestnut","meanings":["Scottish (Renfrewshire and Lanarkshire) and northern Irish: altered form of   Chesney  , shortened from   McChesney  . Its assimilation to the English word <i>chestnut</i> is due to folk etymology, the word itself being first recorded in 1519. The surname was probably taken to Ireland at the time of the 17th-century Plantation of Ulster.","English (Norfolk): probably a variant of <b>Chestney</b> (see   Chaney  ), altered by folk etymological association with the word <i>chestnut</i>."]},{"name":"Chesna","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Chesney  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Radulphus de Chesnay was born in 1024, in Le Quesney, Eure, Upper Normandy, France, his father, Gautier de Cheyney de Casisneto, was 34 and his mother, Gladys Verch Conyn, was 34. He married Gladys verch Rhiwallon about 1043, in Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1086, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1024–1086":"1024–1086","1021–1092":"1021–1092","1044–1086":"1044–1086","0990–Male":"0990–Surnud","0990–1097":"0990–1097","1024":"1024","0990":"0990","1044":"1044","1021":"1021","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","about 1043":"umbes 1043","1092":"1092","Glenham, Lincolnshire England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Le Quesney, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandy, France":"L